European Defence and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Maybe it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of Europe's intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors, combined, have led me to the conviction that Europe represents a single political entity, whose security is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europes forever  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, one less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is an error.
It's as if a part of a room could be heated while it remained cold in the other part.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event echoes across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest – a series of essential tasks must be tackled, both within the new democracies and within the European as well as the Atlantic community.
Firstly, Europe must promote a sense of community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from the top.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more they are interconnected, the better equipped the new democracies will be for membership in the EU and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will meet those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely linked to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, communities, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the policy of appeasement, which gave up on European solidarity and led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call to vigilance.
We must counter the evil as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if only governments act.
For government policy emerges from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is intensively working on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by the ability to make rapid decisions and to implement joint decisions quickly  reforms that recent developments in Yugoslavia have shown to be necessary.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of European security, require interventions outside the EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate does not come, although an intervention is in the interest of many people, all of Europe, indeed even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
But even more is needed in the field of preventive security, and it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of an expanded European civilization.
Tens of thousands of human lives and enormous material resources could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was only taken timidly.
These failures were the result of various individual internal political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot rely on the US forever, especially not when it comes to European problems.
It must be able to agree on its own solutions.
It is unimaginable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves unable to agree on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its territory but also in areas that may one day join it.
Such EU expansion is only feasible if it is accompanied by a courageous reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the Union.
But I consider this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a permanent endeavor to accelerate and make EU decision-making more transparent.
A point related to institutional reform is the question of how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be outvoted by the larger ones, while still taking into account the size of individual states.
One possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would not be elected directly, but rather from the ranks of the parliaments of the member states.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current parliament – would thus reflect the size of individual member states, while the second chamber would, with an equal number of representatives for each state, increase equality.
At some point, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution would require two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principal powers, and their relationships with one another.
Such a fundamental law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current union into the federal superstate feared by eurosceptics.
However, it would help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see the importance of the EU in their lives, and thus identify with it.
